id data and suggestions for practical intervention for those who study and work to support this population. It highlights the challenges these young women face, as well as the ways in which they successfully negotiate those challenges. The volume includes research on Latinas and their relationships with family, friends, and romantic partners; academics; career goals; identity; lifelong satisfaction; and the ways in which they navigate across cultures and gender roles.Latina Girls is the first book to pull together research on the overall strengths and strategies that characterize Latina adolescents' lives in the U.S. It will be of key interest and practical use to those who study and work with Latina youth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHispanic American teenage girlsxPsychology. 0aHispanic American teenage girlsxSocial conditions. 0aHispanic AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 4aLatinas. 4aacademics. 4aacross. 4acareer. 4acultures. 4afamily. 4afriends. 4agender. 4agoals. 4aidentity. 4aincludes. 4alifelong. 4anavigate. 4apartners. 4arelationships. 4aresearch. 4aroles. 4aromantic. 4asatisfaction. 4atheir. 4athey. 4avolume. 4aways. 4awhich. 4awith. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / Adolescent.2bisacsh1 aDenner, Jill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuzman, Bianca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814785447.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHA